{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum Hamming weight of the product 2023 * n. Since 2023 is not a power of 2, k(n) can be small. This is equivalent to finding the minimum number of ones in a multiple of 2023. This is a classic problem related to the order of 2 modulo the odd part of the number.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Analyze the number 2023. Determine its prime factorization. Check if 2023 is coprime to 2. Verify if there exists an n such that 2023 * n is a power of 2 (which would make k(n) = 1). If not, prove why k(n) cannot be 1 by examining the divisibility of 2^m by 2023."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Investigate if k(n) = 2 is possible. This occurs if 2023 * n = 2^a + 2^b for some integers a > b >= 0. This is equivalent to checking if 2023 divides 2^b * (2^(a-b) + 1). Since 2023 is odd, this simplifies to checking if 2023 divides 2^k + 1 for some k. Test small values of k or use modular arithmetic (specifically checking 2^k mod 7 and 2^k mod 17, since 2023 = 7 * 17^2) to determine if 2^k is congruent to -1 modulo 2023."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_3",
      "instructions": "If k(n) = 2 is impossible, investigate if k(n) = 3 is possible. This occurs if 2023 divides 2^a + 2^b + 2^c. Test the condition 2^x + 2^y + 1 is congruent to 0 modulo 2023 for small x, y. Specifically, check if there exist x, y such that 2^x + 2^y + 1 is a multiple of 7 and a multiple of 289 (17 squared)."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent should combine the results to determine the smallest integer k such that a sum of k powers of 2 is divisible by 2023. Start by ruling out k=1, then k=2, then k=3, and so on, until a valid k is found or a pattern is established."
}

